<h2 class="text-center my-4">Seagrasses of Tubbataha Reef</h2>

<div class="text-center mb-4">
    <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQJJSzZbQMZhFYbZlxp3Etx6IUp-KFhJARLrA&s" alt="Seagrasses of Tubbataha Reef" class="img-fluid custom-img-size" />
</div>

<p class="mb-4">
    While Tubbataha Reef is best known for its coral ecosystems, it also supports seagrass meadows. These underwater flowering plants provide critical habitats and ecological services to the reef system. Seagrasses are vital for the health of Tubbataha's marine ecosystem, sustaining biodiversity, improving water quality, and serving as a carbon sink.
</p>

<h3 class="text-center">Common Seagrass Species in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Enhalus acoroides (Tape Seagrass)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcThfzPuNWbYpPL2ArQAUFY--o9810mSb_RpLQ&s" alt="Tape Seagrass" class="img-fluid custom-img-size" />
        </div>
        <li>Recognizable by its broad, ribbon-like leaves. It forms dense meadows in shallow waters.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Thalassia hemprichii (Spoon Seagrass)</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/606/33348349916_4a16de70c1_b.jpg" alt="Spoon Seagrass" class="img-fluid custom-img-size" />
    </div>
    <p>A common tropical species with flat, spoon-shaped leaves.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Halophila ovalis (Paddle Grass)</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTFm_yXKhqcyJOCznS48_wGcs1cXSwqtjQuBw&s" alt="Paddle Seagrass" class="img-fluid custom-img-size" />
    </div>
    <p>Small, delicate leaves that form sparse meadows, often mixed with other species.</p>
</section>

