    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Halodule species (Needle Seagrass)</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/content_slide_image/public/2020-05/Small_WW2129441.jpg?h=82f92a78&itok=e0P9tclY" alt="Needle Seagrass" class="img-fluid custom-img-size" />
    </div>
    <p>Narrow, grass-like leaves found in shallow waters and intertidal zones.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Interesting Facts About Seagrasses</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Carbon Sequestration</h4>
    <p>Seagrasses are often called the "lungs of the sea" because they absorb large amounts of carbon dioxide and release oxygen.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Biodiversity Hotspots</h4>
    <p>Seagrass meadows provide food and shelter for numerous species, including fish, turtles, dugongs, and invertebrates.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Nursery Grounds</h4>
    <p>Juvenile fish and other marine animals use seagrass meadows as safe nurseries, enhancing fishery productivity.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Wave and Erosion Protection</h4>
    <p>Seagrasses stabilize sediments and act as a buffer against wave action, protecting coastlines.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Indicator of Ecosystem Health</h4>
    <p>Healthy seagrass meadows indicate a balanced and thriving marine ecosystem, while their decline signals ecological stress.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Conservation Practices to Protect Seagrasses</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Avoid Damaging Seagrasses</h4>
    <p>When snorkeling or boating, avoid anchoring in seagrass meadows to prevent uprooting or damaging plants.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Minimize Plastic and Chemical Use</h4>
    <p>Seagrasses are sensitive to pollutants like plastics, fertilizers, and chemicals, which reduce water quality.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Participate in Clean-Up Drives</h4>
    <p>Removing marine debris helps maintain healthy seagrass meadows.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Support Awareness Campaigns</h4>
    <p>Educate others about the importance of seagrasses in sustaining marine ecosystems.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Threats to Seagrass in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Climate Change</h4>
    <p>Rising sea temperatures and ocean acidification hinder seagrass growth and reproduction.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Pollution</h4>
    <p>Agricultural runoff, sediments, and plastics block sunlight and degrade water quality.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Physical Damage</h4>
    <p>Anchors, boat propellers, and trampling can uproot and destroy seagrass beds.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Overfishing and Habitat Destruction</h4>
    <p>Unsustainable fishing practices, such as the use of bottom-dragging nets, can devastate seagrass meadows.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Invasive Species</h4>
    <p>Non-native species can compete with native seagrasses, altering the ecosystem balance.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Why Seagrass Conservation Matters</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Supports Marine Life</h4>
    <p>Provides critical habitats for iconic species like green sea turtles and dugongs, both of which are seen in Tubbataha Reef.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Enhances Coral Reef Health</h4>
    <p>Seagrasses improve water clarity and quality, benefiting adjacent coral reefs.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Mitigates Climate Change</h4>
    <p>Seagrass meadows are among the most efficient carbon sinks, absorbing carbon dioxide and storing it in sediments.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Economic Importance</h4>
    <p>Seagrasses sustain fisheries and eco-tourism industries by supporting fish populations and biodiversity.</p>
</section>

